Myth: The bonfire world roared, its heat threatening to scorch the very stars Solara resided among. The Shadows she had painted gathered at the edges of the flame-feathered birds' flight, but the fire was too voracious; it ate the darkness. Solara realized that balance could not be forced by opposition alone. The fire needed a vessel, not an enemy.

She reached down and gathered the mists rising from the melting frost. Mixing them with the cool, silent silver of moonlight, she created the Nightblooms. These were no ordinary flowers; their petals were made of crystallized silence. They did not bloom in the sun but opened only when the flame-birds roosted, absorbing the excess heat of the day into their glowing cores. They drank the fire and exhaled a cooling, fragrant steam. Now, the Oak’s forge powered the world, but the Nightblooms ensured it did not burn itself to ash, creating a rhythm of burning exertion and cool, silver recovery.

